gdom","Farnworth, Lancashire, England":"Farnworth, Lancashire, England","Thorganbye, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cook","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cookson","meanings":["English (Lancashire): from Middle English <i>cok</i> ‘cook’ or the surname <i>Cook</i> + <i>son</i>, denoting either ‘son of (the) cook’ or ‘son of (a man called) Cook’. See   Cook  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Coke","meanings":["English: variant of   Cook   or   Cocke  .","Americanized form of German   Koke   or   Koch  ."]},{"name":"Kuhar","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: occupational name for a cook, from <i>kuhar</i>, a derivative of <i>kuhati</i> ‘to cook’. Compare   Cook  .","Americanized form of Slovak <b>Kuchár</b> ‘cook’ (see   Kuchar  ) and of its Ukrainian and Rusyn cognate <b>Kukhar</b>."]},{"name":"Cooke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."]},{"name":"Kew","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>queu</i>, <i>keu</i>, <i>kieu</i>, <i>cu</i> ‘cook’, i.e. one who sold cooked meat, keeper of an eating house.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Caieu, a lost town in northern France, in the vicinity of Boulogne-sur-Mer.","Irish: shortened Ulster variant of   McHugh  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Cook was born in 1513, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Lomas on 19 November 1555, in Farnworth, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 4 daughters. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1513–":"1513–Surnud","1513–Male":"1513–Surnud","1539–Female"